Analysis.name: Miscarriage – low risk of bias (odds ratio, random-effects)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
Participants were randomized using block randomization and various block sizes of 2, 4 or 8. Randomization was performed by an independent study coordinator via telephone, using a computer-generated random list.
We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int:
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage.
The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo:
The outcome was defined and measured properly. Its definition was also the same for both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result:
The outcome of miscarriage was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Miscarriage was defined as the pregnancy loss before 12 weeks of gestation. The same time point was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.
Overall.bias.support:

We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage.
The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis.

The outcome was defined and measured properly.
Its definition was also the same for both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).

The outcome of miscarriage was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Miscarriage was defined as the pregnancy loss before 12 weeks of gestation. The same time point was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.

Analysis.name: Miscarriage – low risk of bias (odds ratio, random-effects)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
Participants were randomized using block randomization and a variable block size of 4 or 6. Randomization was performed using a computer-generated random list. Opaque sealed envelopes with randomized assigned groups printed inside were numbered consecutively. The randomization list and envelopes were prepared by an independent statistician at the Research Centre of Clinical Epidemiology of Peking University Third Hospital.
We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int:
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage (NCT03463772).
The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram (only one participant from the IVF group).
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo:
The outcome was defined and measured properly.
No, during the nature of the outcome. Its definition was also the same for both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result:
The outcome of miscarriage was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Miscarriage was defined as the spontaneous loss of an intrauterine pregnancy prior to 28 completed weeks of gestational age. The same time point was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.
Overall.bias.support:

We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Blinding was not used in this trial.

There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram (only one participant from the IVF group).

The outcome was defined and measured properly.
Its definition was also the same for both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).

The outcome of miscarriage was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Miscarriage was defined as the spontaneous loss of an intrauterine pregnancy prior to 28 completed weeks of gestational age. The same time point was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.

Analysis.name: Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome – low risk of bias (odds ratio, random-effects)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
Participants were randomized using block randomization and various block sizes of 2, 4 or 8. Randomization was performed by an independent study coordinator via telephone, using a computer-generated random list.
We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int:
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage. The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram.
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo:
The outcome was defined and measured properly.
Its definition was the same for both groups. Routine assessments for OHSS were performed on day 3 post oocyte retrieval in both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result:
The outcome of OHSS was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Moderate or severe ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome was classified using the flow diagram by Humaidan et al. for use in clinical trial settings. The same method was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.
Overall.bias.support:
Participants were randomized using block randomization and various block sizes of 2, 4 or 8. Randomization was performed by an independent study coordinator via telephone, using a computer-generated random list.
We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage.
The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis. There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram.

The outcome was defined and measured properly.
Its definition was the same for both groups. Routine assessments for OHSS were performed on day 3 post oocyte retrieval in both groups.
The outcome assessors were blinded (also during the interim analysis of the results).

The outcome of OHSS was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
Moderate or severe ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome was classified using the flow diagram by Humaidan et al. for use in clinical trial settings. The same method was used for the definition in both groups.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.

Analysis.name: Ovarian hyperstimulation syndrome – low risk of bias (odds ratio, random-effects)
Bias.arising.from.the.randomization.proc:
Participants were randomized using block randomization and a variable block size of 4 or 6. Randomization was performed using a computer-generated random list. Opaque sealed envelopes with randomized assigned groups printed inside were numbered consecutively. We found no significant and unexpected baseline differences between the two intervention groups.
Bias.due.to.deviations.from.intended.int:
Blinding was not used in this trial.
The interventions were implemented as described at protocol stage (NCT03463772).
The outcomes were analyzed on both an intention-to-treat and a per-protocol basis.
Bias.due.to.missing.outcome.data.support: There was no important loss to follow-up as per the flow diagram (only one participant from the IVF group).
Bias.in.measurement.of.the.outcome.suppo:
The outcome was defined and measured properly.
It was diagnosed by ultrasound, blood testing, and physical examination according to the RCOG guideline, in both groups.
The responsible statistician was independent from the investigator team.
Bias.in.selection.of.the.reported.result:
The outcome of OHSS was prespecified at protocol stage. The authors explicitly described their analysis plan a priori.
The OHSS was defined as an exaggerated systemic response to ovarian stimulation characterized by a wide spectrum of clinical and laboratory manifestations. It was classified as mild, moderate or severe according to the degree of abdominal distention, ovarian enlargement, respiratory hemodynamics and metabolic complications, as per the RCOG guideline.
We found no indications of selective reporting in the context of multiple eligible analyses of the data.
